textDisplay: +Steven Clark 4. Ultimately what holds all businesses in a libertarian  society accountable are three things: 1. The law. 2. the consumer and 3.  the market itself. There are still laws in place for a libertarian society,  you cant commit fraud, or murder or screw over people for no reason. What  those laws are depends on the judicial system you create. Largely who  enforces those laws are other private organizations, other businesses and  consumers who don't want to be cheated. Also in a libertarian society, the  consumer has significantly more market power. The consumer's choice  influences the demand for a product and therefore the price of most goods  as well. If the majority of people are not willing to buy cars for $50,000,  the company must make changes to fit the demand. There is no other force in  place to establish subsidies for a company as a cushion. Lastly the market  itself makes corrections when something is wrong. if you make a poor  decision there is no safeguard to keep you steady. Your stock falls and  your investors want their money. If you overvalue your company through  fraud the market corrects your mistake and devalues your company below what  you are worth. By doing so investors pull out and your company falls to the  ground.
